explanation:
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: The source shows OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET/lookup calling this; its semantics (validation, possible side effects or error handling) determine whether the table lookup or any code around it is removable.
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: The macro/inline performing the object-table access may hide checks or side effects; you must know its expansion to decide if the assignment to impl or the lookup is dead.
OS_impl_queue_table: The table object layout and contents determine whether the lookup yields a valid impl or causes different behavior; needed to see if subsequent uses of impl are meaningful.
OS_impl_queue_internal_record_t: Definition (particularly the type and meaning of the 'id' field) is required to know what impl->id refers to and whether reading it has observable effects.
OS_object_token_t: The token type and how it is dereferenced/used by the lookup can introduce side effects or validation that affect reachability/necessity of the lookup code.
mq_timedsend: The call is the core operation in the function; need its detailed behavior (side effects, errno semantics, whether it uses ts) to judge if the call/loop is removable (dead).
mqd_t: The type of impl->id (mqd_t) and its semantics matter to know whether accesses to impl->id or attempts to send on it have side effects.
errno: The code branches on errno values set by mq_timedsend; knowing errno behavior is essential to determine whether the conditional branches (and their assignments) are reachable/observable.
EINTR: Loop retry condition depends on EINTR; you must know when mq_timedsend can set EINTR to determine if the retry loop is required or could be considered redundant.
ETIMEDOUT: One branch returns OS_QUEUE_FULL when errno==ETIMEDOUT; need to know whether mq_timedsend can produce this to decide if that branch is live.
memset: Used to initialize ts; need to know if this initialization has any observable effect (i.e., whether ts is actually used by mq_timedsend) to decide if the memset is dead.
struct timespec: Definition and semantics (absolute vs relative timeout) are required because ts is passed to mq_timedsend; this affects whether the memset and ts variable are necessary.
OS_SUCCESS: Return value used on success; to judge whether removing a branch/assignment would alter program behavior you must know the meaning/usage of these status codes.
OS_QUEUE_FULL: Same as above, used for the timeout branch; needed to determine whether that branch has observable effect outside the function.
OS_ERROR: Same as above for the generic error branch; required to evaluate whether assignment to return_code in that branch is observable.
